a-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-18-full-sweep-skirt-and-trapeze-skirt-with-circular-folds/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-18-full-sweep-skirt-and-trapeze-skirt-with-circular-folds/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T17:23:06+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:42:55+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 18. Full Sweep Skirt and Trapeze Skirt with Circular Folds."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 18. Full Sweep Skirt and Trapeze Skirt with Circular Folds."><meta itemprop="description" content="What are we supposed to do if we want to make beautiful folds on a full skirt like here in the picture?"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 18. Full Sweep Skirt and Trapeze Skirt with Circular Folds.</h1><p><strong>What are we supposed to do if we want to make beautiful folds on a full skirt like here in the picture?</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us do calculations for a full sweep skirt and see what we get. </strong></p><p><strong>We will use the same measurements we used for the half-circle skirt: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference − 37cm,</p><p>- Skirt Length – 56cm,</p><p>- Fold Depth – 3cm.</p><p><strong>All calculations are done in half scale the same way as for the half-circle skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>Waist opening radius:</strong></p><p><strong>R =</strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image004.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp; ≈ 18cm</strong></p><p><strong>Large radius R(L) for cutting the bottom edge of the full sweep skirt: </strong></p><p><strong>R(L) = 18cm + 56cm = 74cm</strong></p><p><strong>Consequently, the length of our full sweep skirt with folds (L1) is as follows:</strong></p><p><strong>L1 = </strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image006.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;х R(L) = 2 х 3.14 х 74cm = 465cm</strong></p><p><strong>We have chosen a full petticoat with a 210cm long bottom hoop for our skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>Here is how much needs to be added to the hem length to account for the folds in this case: </strong></p><p><strong>465cm – 210cm = 255cm </strong></p><p>There is a significant difference in the added value: 75cm for the half-circle skirt as compared to 255cm for the full sweep skirt.</p><p><strong>And now let us find the biggest possible depth of fold along the hem of the full sweep skirt: </strong></p><p><strong>255cm / 12 / 2 = 11cm</strong></p><p><strong>As we can see, the fold depth on our full sweep skirt makes 11cm even with a full petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>There are several ways to reduce the fold depth along the hem of the skirt if you feel like it is too big. </strong></p><p><strong>Firstly,</strong> you can increase the bottom circumference of the petticoat, i.e. use a petticoat with a longer bottom hoop (ours is 210cm long in half scale).</p><p><strong>Secondly,</strong> you can use a little less fabric for the skirt itself: for example, make it three quarters of a circle instead of a full circle to cut the front and the back as three eights of a circle and not as half circles.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We need to re-calculate it in this case though. It does not take much time. </strong>All calculations are done the same way, except you replace<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image006.png" alt="">&nbsp; with<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image010.png" alt=""></p><p>We will talk about <strong>calculating ¾ circle skirts in more detail </strong>in the chapter dedicated to the automatic calculation tables. I will introduce you to all key formulae. And right now, I am just setting the right direction for your work.</p><p><strong>You can always choose the right size of pieces for cutting this or that skirt based on the properties of fabric and the desired results. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us look at a situation when the skirt is supposed to have folds at the front and a train at the back. </strong></p><p><strong>There is no universal answer as to what size your skirt pieces should be. The final decision depends on many factors. </strong>But I can definitely say that a half-circle skirt will give you too much fabric at the back!</p><p><strong>In other words, </strong>if you cut a skirt with circular folds as a full circle, then one half of the circle will fall upon the front of the skirt and the other half – upon the back. But if you want to have nice deep folds at the front and a train at the back, then a half-circle piece like that will be too massive for the back.</p><p><strong>A train made of a half-circle piece with folds will look really bulky even if it is sewn with thin fabric! </strong>Let me try to explain you what will happen in this case.</p><p>The train with folds will look fine going along the back and down to the floor even if it is sewn with thin fabric. But the folds will start getting distorted as soon as the fabric of the train settles down upon the floor. They will only preserve their beautiful shape as long as the fabric is hanging down. The same folds will fall apart chaotically in the part of the train dragging along the floor. It will look no good.</p><p><strong>For this reason, the back piece with a train is normally cut as one quarter or three eights of a circle with folds along the waistline. </strong></p><p><strong>As for me, </strong>I cut the front of such skirts as a half circle to get nice large folds and cut the back with the train as three eights of a circle. This requires doing very precise calculations to make the length of the top edge correspond with the Waist Circumference.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>In addition, just look </strong>how lovely half-circle and full-circle skirts look with circular folds along the full length when they are knee-long or mid-calf-long.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We have discussed how to make a skirt with beautiful deep folds. </strong>The skirt turns out very full in this case though.</p><p><strong>What to do if your client does not want her skirt to be that full but does want to keep those beautiful deep folds? </strong></p><p>You will have to use a petticoat with a very small bottom hoop <strong>if the skirt was cut based on a half circle. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And if it was cut based on a full circle, </strong>then the petticoat and the skirt itself will be very full.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>But we want something medium, for example, a petticoat with a 140cm long bottom hoop (in half scale). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>You need to go in the opposite direction to solve this problem: first choose a petticoat of the desired size and then do all calculations. </strong></p><p><strong>I will show you how to calculate the pattern of a skirt which will fit a petticoat with a 140cm long bottom hoop. </strong></p><p><strong>In this case, you can design your skirt based on the trapeze skirt pattern. </strong>The first thing you need to do is calculate all parameters of the folds, as well as the lengths of the top edge and the bottom edge of the skirt.</p><p><strong>Let us start from calculating the bottom width of the fold. </strong></p><p>We know that the hem of our half-scale skirt is 140cm long. We can determine the width of the face part of the fold by dividing the full circumference by twelve (the number of folds):</p><p><strong>140cm / 12 = 11cm</strong></p><p><strong>Next, we add the calculated fold width multiplied by two to 140cm to find the hem length with folds included: </strong></p><p><strong>140cm + 11cm х 2 х 12 = 140cm + 264cm = 404cm</strong></p><p><strong>As the result, the full length of the hem including 11cm wide folds is 404cm.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>We will use the flared (trapeze) skirt pattern for cutting our skirt. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is easy to calculate the length of the bottom edge of the piece knowing the total hem length: </strong></p><p><strong>404cm / 4 = 101cm</strong></p><p><strong>The length of the top edge of the piece is calculated the same way considering that each fold has a width of 3cm at the top and the waistline is 37cm long: </strong></p><p><strong>(37cm + 3cm х 2 х 12) / 4 ≈ 27cm</strong></p><p><strong>We have made a pattern of a trapeze skirt piece and the garment sewn after it will fully comply with our client’s requirements: it will be a skirt of modest fullness with deep folds. </strong></p><p><strong>There are other modifications of skirts cut based on the flared or trapeze skirt pattern. </strong></p><p>There is, <strong>for example</strong>, a pretty type of a skirt with folds at the waist which gradually open towards the bottom forming a fully smooth surface.</p><p>If you want to sew a skirt like that, you should account for the desired hem length and number of folds around the waist in the calculations.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2018.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I assume I have explained the key points about cutting skirts with circular folds. You will no longer have to make guesses when you see a picture of a similar garment.</strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>